  "prompt": "Why is Sensory Overload painful?",
  "response": "Sensory overload can be painful due to several neurological and physiological reasons:\n\n1. Neurological Processing\n- The brain becomes overwhelmed by too much sensory input\n- Neurotransmitters get overstimulated\n- Neural pathways become overly activated\n\n2. Physiological Stress Response\n- Triggers fight-or-flight response\n- Increases cortisol and stress hormone levels\n- Causes muscle tension and physical discomfort\n\n3. Nervous System Sensitivity\n- Some people have more sensitive nervous systems\n- Overstimulation can cause actual physical pain\n- Neurodivergent individuals (like those with autism) may experience this more intensely\n\n4. Cognitive Strain\n- Brain expends excessive energy trying to process multiple stimuli\n- Mental exhaustion can translate to physical discomfort\n- Creates a sense of being overwhelmed\n\n5. Sensory Processing Differences\n- Some individuals have heightened sensory perception\n- Normal stimuli can feel intense or painful\n- Differences in how sensory information is interpreted\n\nThe pain is essentially the body's protective mechanism signaling that the current sensory environment is too intense and potentially harmful, prompting a need to reduce stimulation.",
